gagement%22%3A32%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fworld-europe-68378736%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww-bbc-co-uk.cdn.ampproject.org%2Fc%2Fs%2Fwww.bbc.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fworld-europe-68378736.amp%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fworld-europe-68378736.amp%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Scientists%20Discover%20240-Million-Year-Old%20%26quot%3BChinese%20Dragon%26quot%3B%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cp%3EScientists%20in%20Scotland%20have%20made%20a%20remarkable%20discovery%20of%20a%20240-million-year-old%20%26quot%3BChinese%20dragon%26quot%3B%20fossil.%20According%20to%20the%20%3Cem%3EBBC%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20the%2016-feet-long%20fossil%20belongs%20to%20a%20long%20aquatic%20reptile%20from%20the%20Triassic%20period.%20The%20species%20is%20called%20Dinocephalosaurus%20orientalis%2C%20and%20has%20been%20dubbed%20%26quot%3Bdragon%26quot%3B%20because%20of%20its%20extremely%20long%20neck.%20The%20discovery%20was%20made%20by%20an%20international%20team%20and%20displayed%20it%20at%20the%20National%20Museums%20Scotland.%20The%20fossil%20was%20found%20in%20Guizhou%20Province%20in%20southern%20China%2C%20as%20per%20an%20%3Cem%3EABC%20News%3C%2Fem%3E%20report.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EDr%20Nick%20Fraser%2C%20who%20was%20part%20of%20the%20international%20team%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.com%2Fnews%2Fscience-environment-68374520%5C%22%3Etold%20the%20%3Cem%3EBBC%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20the%20fossil%20belongs%20to%20%26quot%3Ba%20very%20strange%20animal%26quot%3B.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20had%20flipper-like%20limbs%20and%20its%20neck%20is%20longer%20than%20its%20body%20and%20tail%20combined%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20added.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20long%20neck%20could%20have%20allowed%20Dinocephalosaurus%20orientalis%20to%20search%20for%20food%20in%20crevices%20under%20the%20water.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThis%20discovery%20just%20adds%20to%20the%20weirdness%20of%20the%20Triassic.%20And%20every%20time%20we%20look%20in%20these%20deposits%2C%20we%20find%20something%20new%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Dr%20Fraser.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EScientists%20said%20the%20animal%20is%20similar%20to%20Tanystropheus%20hydroides%2C%20a%20marine%20reptile%20from%20the%20Middle%20Triassic%20period.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BBoth%20reptiles%20were%20of%20similar%20size%20and%20have%20several%20features%20of%20the%20skull%20in%20common%2C%20including%20a%20fish-trap%20type%20of%20dentition.%20However%2C%20Dinocephalosaurus%20is%20unique%20in%20possessing%20many%20more%20vertebrae%20both%20in%20the%20neck%20and%20in%20the%20torso%2C%20giving%20the%20animal%20a%20much%20more%20snake-like%20appearance%2C%26quot%3B%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fabcnews.go.com%2FInternational%2Fscientists-announce-discovery-strange-240-million-year-chinese%2Fstory%3Fid%3D107473094%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EABC%20News%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20quoted%20the%20research%20team%20as%20saying.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20international%20team%20also%20said%20that%20the%20reptile%20was%20%26quot%3Bclearly%20very%20well%20adapted%20to%20an%20oceanic%20lifestyle%2C%26quot%3B%20as%20indicated%20by%20the%20flippered%20limbs%20and%20%26quot%3Bexquisitely%20preserved%26quot%3B%20fishes%20in%20its%20stomach%20region.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20team%20includes%20experts%20from%20Scotland%2C%20Germany%2C%20the%20United%20States%20and%20China.%20They%20studied%20the%20fossil%20over%20the%20course%20of%20ten%20years%20at%20the%20Institute%20of%20Vertebrate%20Palaeontology%20and%20Palaeoanthropology%20in%20Beijing%20but%20made%20their%20announcement%20public%20on%20Friday.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20study%20has%20been%20published%20in%20the%20journal%20'Earth%20and%20Environmental%20Science%3A%20Transactions%20of%20the%20Royal%20Society%20of%20Edinburgh'.%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1708691220000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fc.ndtvimg.com%2F2024-02%2Fag09e8e_dragon-fossil_625x300_23_February_24.jpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A